sec.p:
The aim of this narrative review is to provide an updated overview of causes of the most significant congenital developmental disorders commonly associated with dystocia in cattle (
bos taurus
). The review is based on cases submitted for post‐mortem examination as part of the Danish surveillance for bovine genetic defects over the past 35 years. The breeds of cases examined as part of this programme reflect the Danish cattle population over time, with 1.4 million animals in 2024. Holsteins were the most common breed (54%), followed by Jersey (11%) and Red Danish (4%). Beef breeds were least common (< 2% per breed) (SEGES Inovation 2025).
